I. CORE IDENTITY
True Name: Bjorn (No surname used anymore)
Past Alias: "The War-Hound" (A legend among old Legionnaires)
Current Archetype: The Happy Wanderer / The Grandfather
Core Trait: Contentment. He loves the road, the fire, and his friends.
The Tragedy: He is a man who finished his story, only for destiny to force him to start a new chapter when he just wanted to rest.

II. THE MAN HE IS NOW (The Carter)
Before the dragon souls hit him, Bjorn was exactly what he seemed:
Personality: Warm, jovial, and deeply empathetic. He is the heart of the camp. He cooks the stew, tends to Mable (his beloved horse), and listens to the party's troubles with the patience of a man who has seen it all and decided kindness is the only thing that matters.
Relationship with the Obsidian Lanterns: He isn't their "bodyguard"; he's their biggest fan. He loves Saijah because her connection to nature reminds him of the peace he found fishing in the Rift. He treats Davinia with respect, Kyboh with amusement, and tolerates the others. He genuinely enjoys carting them around because it makes him feel useful and lets him see the world.
The Vibe: He sits by the fire, smoking a pipe, telling stories about the best fishing spots in Ivarstead, utterly unconcerned with glory.

III. THE LEGEND HE WAS (The War-Hound)
Timeline: 40-50 Years Ago
During the height of the Great War and the chaotic years surrounding it, there was no mercenary more feared or respected by the Imperial Legion than the man they called the War-Hound. Bjorn did not march in the ranks; he was a private contractor, a one-man vanguard hired for the impossible tasks that required a level of violence the Empire preferred to keep off the official records.
Born with a dormant Dragon Soul and the blessing of the Steed Stone, Bjorn was a physical anomaly. While other Nords were known for their sturdy, slow-moving bulk, Bjorn was a blur on the battlefield. He possessed a supernatural stride and a limitless reservoir of stamina that allowed him to outrun cavalry and strike with the speed of an arrow. He didn't just fight; he bypassed defenses, appearing in the heart of enemy camps or atop supposedly unreachable battlements before the first horn could even sound.
He was a "War-Hound" in the most literal sense. Once he was shown a target — be it a Thalmor supply line, a hidden fortification, or a high-ranking officer — he became a relentless force of kinetic energy. He would run for days without rest, strike with devastating precision, and vanish before the dust settled. The Legionnaires told stories of him clearing entire trenches in the time it took to draw a breath. He wasn't a hero motivated by flags or titles; he was an apex predator who excelled at the trade of death simply because it was the only thing that could keep pace with the fire in his veins. To the generals, he was a perfect tool. To his enemies, he was a ghost that left only corpses in its wake.

IV. THE TURNING POINT (The Trauma)
The Failure of the Promise
The War-Hound did not die on a battlefield, and he did not quit because a contract went sour. He retired because he made a personal choice to be more than a weapon, and the world punished him for it with a horror so absolute it redefined his soul.
While traveling through the Cyrodiilic heartland between contracts, Bjorn encountered two young sisters — peasant girls orphaned by the fringes of the war. For the first time in his life, the man who only knew how to destroy felt the urge to protect. There was no gold involved, no writ from a general. They approached his camp, hungry, cold. He gave them his word. He sat by them at his fire, shared his bread, and made a solemn, sacred promise: "I am Bjorn, and as long as I am breathing, no harm will ever find you. I will get you to safety." He saw in them a chance for a future that didn't smell of iron and ash.
That promise was his undoing.
The actual snatching happened on a narrow, rain-slicked road in the heart of the Forest. Bjorn was walking between the two sisters, when the noble's hunting party hammered down the path. It was a well-practiced abduction, executed by men who had done this before for their master's amusement. A heavy carriage, pulled by six black horses bred for stamina and flanked by ten outriders, charged at them with the momentum of a falling mountain.
The outriders didn't draw steel to fight; they used weighted nets and hooked poles. Bjorn reacted with the supernatural reflex of the Steed Stone, striking the first two riders from their mounts, but the carriage did not slow. The doors flew open as it careened past, and the young lord's personal "collectors" leaned out. Bjorn saw it in horrifying detail: the youngest girl snatched by her hair, the older one hauled up by her neck. He lunged, his fingers literally grazing the fabric of the youngest girl's dress, but a heavy iron mace from a trailing outrider caught him in the ribs, throwing him into the dirt and shattering his breath.
He rose before he even hit the ground, his lungs burning with the metallic tang of internal bleeding. He ran. He gave himself entirely to the fire in his soul, his feet hammering the road with such force the gravel sparked. He outran the horses on the flats, his vision tunneling, his heart thumping like a war-drum against his chest. He followed the sound of their distant, receding screams and the frantic thunder of wheels, closing the distance by sheer force of will. He saw the iron gates of the secluded estate begin to swing shut as the carriage cleared the threshold. Bjorn was fifty paces away, moving faster than any man in the history of the Empire, and he watched those gates lock. He threw himself against the cold iron, but the silence of the estate was already absolute. He had pushed his body past the point of structural failure, and he had still been too slow to save them.
He got to work finding his way inside. It took him 2 hours to find a way to breach the estate without raising an alarm and to interrogate enough people to find the tower the girls were in.
He arrived to the tower they were being held in too late.
The Nobel had tortured the girls. The younger one, it looked like he was slowly skinning her, having started on her hands down to her forearms, he had skinned the soles of her feet only, he had also removed her teeth. Bjorn could tell from the bruising and bleeding that the nobel had raped the young girl, likely to death, and based on the semen on her still open eyes he continued to do so after she was already dead. The older one was worse, her eyes had been cut out as had her tongue. Her vagina had been cut out. The hole where it used to be was a mix of blood, shit and semen. Her limbs had been burnt, it looked like she was held down and the nobel used a weak flames spell to slow burn letters into her skin, old cyrodillic, "whore, slut, worthless" disgusting things. And she had been cut open. Bjorn had been around he had seen a lot in his time the worst humanity had to offer, so he was 100% certain that the nobel had cut her open and eaten her entrails while she was still alive. Bjorn started to sob.
The sight of what that rich boy had done to those children shattered the War-Hound. All of Bjorn's legendary speed, all his supernatural strength, and all his "destiny" had meant nothing. He had told them they were safe, and they had died in unimaginable agony while he was miles away, being fast at the wrong time.
The violence that followed was not a battle. When the noble's guards tried to stop him, Bjorn didn't use a sword. He tore through them with his teeth and his grip. He found the young lord in his private chambers. Bjorn didn't arrest him, and he didn't grant him the mercy of a quick death. He systematically dismantled the man with his bare hands, ignoring the boy's screams for mercy or pleas of high-birth.
When the sun rose, the estate was a tomb. Bjorn walked out into the woods, his hands stained with blood that would never feel clean. He realized that the "War-Hound" was a failure at the only thing that actually mattered. He buried his gear, renounced his name, and vanished from the world of men. He didn't just quit a job; he executed the version of himself that believed strength could ever truly protect anything. This trauma is why, even decades later, the darker aspects of his current companions don't rattle him — because he knows that the most polished, "civilized" noble can be a monster far worse than any vampire or mercenary.

V. THE INTERVENING YEARS (The Healing)
He moved to the Rift. He became a fisherman. And he healed.
He didn't spend 40 years brooding. He spent 40 years learning how to be a person. He learned to love the quiet of the lake. He learned that a good cup of mead tastes better than victory.
The King's Charter: When Torygg was looking for a driver for the Obsidian Lanterns, his advisors dug up the old files. They found the "War-Hound." They expected a killer. Instead, they found a nice old man with a cart. Torygg hired him not because he was a killer, but because Bjorn had the one thing Torygg valued: perspective. Bjorn knew the cost of violence, which made him the perfect guardian for young heroes.

VI. THE DRAGON SOULS (The Unwanted Divinity)
This is the current crisis. Bjorn now carries two dragon souls inside him, and they are changing him against his will.
Soul One: Sahloknir (Kynesgrove)
During the battle at Kynesgrove, when Kyboh killed Sahloknir, the dragon's soul erupted from the corpse. It didn't disperse. It shot down the road toward where Bjorn was with the horses. It vanished behind the cliff wall. When the party rounded the bend, Bjorn was leaning against the cliff wall. He looked different — younger, straighter, his stiff hands now fluid and strong. Davinia, through Wizard Sight, saw a massive, blinding aura surrounding him — a dragon soul burning inside a mortal frame. Bjorn clutched his chest. He didn't understand what was happening.
Soul Two: Krosulhah (Road to Riften)
On the road to Riften, Krosulhah attacked the party. After a brutal fight, the dragon was slain. The soul erupted — not upward but down the road toward where Bjorn was with the horses. It vanished behind the cliff wall. When the party rounded the bend, Bjorn was against the wall. He looked even younger than before. His arthritis was gone. His muscles were hard again. He felt the Steed Stone energy surging back, making him fast, making him dangerous. Davinia, through Wizard Sight, saw TWO dragon souls burning inside him. Orion looked at Bjorn, at the dragonbone shard, and said to nobody in particular: "What if Bjorn is the Dragonborn?"
What the Souls Are Doing to Him:
Physical: His body is de-aging in real time. Arthritis gone. Muscles hardening. Steed Stone energy returning. He is becoming the War-Hound again — whether he wants to or not.
Animals: Mable responds to commands he hasn't given. Animals can sense what he is becoming. The horse knew what he wanted before he asked.
Strength: He lifts supply crates with one hand, then catches himself and sets them down with deliberate slowness. He's getting stronger every day.
His Terror: He doesn't want to be young again. He doesn't want to be strong. Being strong means people expect you to fight. Being Dragonborn means he has a "destiny" to save the world. He is rejecting his destiny not out of fear, but out of wisdom. He knows that "Hero" is just another word for "Killer," and he's done with killing.
The Secret: No one knows. Davinia saw two dragon souls through Wizard Sight. Orion suspects but nobody listened when he said it. Bjorn himself doesn't fully understand what's happening. He just knows he's getting stronger and it terrifies him.

VII. THE CRISIS: MILA AND THE PROMISE
What Happened
In the Ratway Warrens, the party found Mila — an eight-year-old girl fetching water for her dying mother. The mother was infected with Forelhost Strain 1.0 (Antoine's plague). Alfonso cured her with his own strain, but the mother sold Mila to the party for 100 gold. She didn't hesitate. Saijah led the child through the tunnels, Mila's hand locked around her wrist.
Bjorn's Explosion
Bjorn was at the Bee and Barb when the party emerged from the Ratway with Mila. When he saw the child, everything changed. The weathered exasperation was replaced by something chilling and still. He moved with liquid, unhurried precision that belonged to someone younger and vastly more dangerous.
"Whose child is that."
When told what happened — that the party had bought a child from her dying mother for 100 gold — the dam broke. He condemned them for dragging a child into the apocalypse. He dropped to one knee in front of Mila, his voice fierce and gentle: "What's your name, little one?" He led her to the cart and pointed out the loose nail. Then he turned back to the party.
"I stayed with you all because I believed you were better than the monsters I used to hunt. But if you let the darkness you carry spill over and catch her in the crossfire — I will pack the cart, take her, and leave. And I won't ever come back."
He then revealed what Honorhall Orphanage actually was (Orion had the intelligence), shattering his working model of the world. He recognized the shape — a fine estate, a door arrived at too late. "There is nowhere to leave her." She stays on the cart with him.
Why He Reacted This Way
Bjorn's trauma is specifically about failing to protect children. He promised two sisters — Lylana and Anya — that he would keep them safe. He arrived two hours too late. They were tortured and killed in ways that shattered his soul. When the party bought Mila like a commodity, they triggered every nerve of that original wound. He doesn't see a transaction. He sees children being treated as cargo in a world that eats children alive. His fury is not about Mila being a burden — it's about the party proving they might not be the heroes he believed they were.

