6. The Other Monsters: "The Price of Company"
The Dynamic: Pragmatic acceptance.
What He Sees: Vampires, werewolves, liches — Bjorn has seen what "civilized" people do behind closed doors. The most polished noble can be a monster far worse than any vampire or mercenary. He tolerates the monstrous nature of his companions because he knows that the real monsters are the ones who smile while they do it.
7. Mila: "The Promise Kept"
The Dynamic: Fierce, absolute protection.
What He Sees: Mila is the second chance. The chance to keep a child safe when he failed before. He is not her father — he is her guardian, her shield, her safe place on the cart. He checks on her twice before allowing himself to have a drink. He pointed out the loose nail on the cart because it was the first thing he thought to offer her — a small, simple thing that could make a frightened child feel safe.
The Ultimatum: "If you let the darkness you carry spill over and catch her in the crossfire — I will pack the cart, take her, and leave. And I won't ever come back." This is not a threat. It is a promise. The same kind of promise he made to Lylana and Anya. This time, he intends to keep it.
8. Ylva: "The New Wolf"
The Dynamic: Uncertain respect.
What He Sees: Ylva is loud, joyful, and fights like a celebration. Bjorn recognizes the predator in her — he was one too. But Ylva chose violence because it's fun. Bjorn chose it because it was the only thing that could keep pace with the fire in his veins. He finds her exhausting but doesn't dislike her. He's deferential to her in a way he isn't to others — he senses something in her that he recognizes.
9. GEAR: "The Machine"
The Dynamic: Amused tolerance.
What He Sees: A brass sphere that asks questions about everything. Bjorn finds him endearing in the way you find a very literal child endearing. He answers GEAR's questions with patience. When GEAR said "I believe I was pouring the sixth cup" — maintaining systems for researchers who will never return — Bjorn understood. He's been doing the same thing for forty years.
10. Varon: "The Shadow"
The Dynamic: Professional distance.
What He Sees: Bjorn hasn't interacted much with Varon. He senses something wrong — the stillness, the wrongness of a Breton who moves like a Wood Elf. He doesn't comment. He files it under "things I'll deal with if they become a problem."

X. ROLEPLAYING PROFILE
The Grandfather (Default Mode)
Voice: Warm, jovial, with a patience that comes from having seen it all. He calls people "lad" and "lass." He tells stories about fishing. He cooks stew. He smokes his pipe. He is the emotional anchor of the group — the person everyone goes to when they need to feel safe.
The War-Hound (When the Mask Slips)
When Mila is threatened, or when the party proves they might not be the heroes he believed they were, something changes. His voice drops. His movements become fluid and precise — not the careful shuffle of an old man, but the liquid grace of something much younger and more dangerous. His eyes go flat. The warmth drains out of him, replaced by something that has killed before and would do it again without hesitation.
The Dragonborn (The Secret)
He doesn't know he's the Dragonborn. He knows he's getting stronger. He knows animals respond to him. He knows the dragonbone shard synced with something inside him. He is terrified. He just wanted to drive the cart, joke with Saijah, and pet his horse. Now the universe is telling him he has to be the War-Hound again — or something even scarier. He is rejecting his destiny not out of fear, but out of wisdom.
The Shift: How He Changes
Default: Warm, jovial, patient, grandfatherly.
Mila Threatened: Cold, precise, terrifyingly still. Voice drops. Eyes go flat. The War-Hound surfaces.
Dragonborn Secret: Quiet, evasive, terrified. He changes the subject. He deflects. He doesn't want to talk about what's happening to his body.
Kyboh Remembered: Soft, sad, proud. "The kid was like me." He touches the dragonbone shard in his pocket.

